            <div class="col-md-4">
                <h3 class="my-3">Overview</h3>
                <p>The Bhagalpur Museum, established on November 11, 1976, is a significant cultural and historical institution located in Bhagalpur, Bihar, India. Renowned for its extensive collection of artifacts and artworks spanning various phases of history, the museum attracts students, tourists, researchers, and trainee archaeologists from across the country.</p>
                <h3 class="my-3">Historical Background</h3>
                <p>Bhagalpur, once part of the ancient Anga Kingdom, is a city with a rich historical background. The city is mentioned in ancient religious and secular texts, highlighting its historical and cultural importance. The Bhagalpur Museum plays a crucial role in preserving and showcasing the city's heritage, offering a glimpse into its past through its diverse collection of artifacts.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-4">
                <h3 class="my-3">Collection and Exhibits</h3>
                <p>The museum houses artifacts dating back to the 6th and 7th centuries, with many unique and stylistically distinct statues. The collection includes:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Buddha Statue:</b> A remarkable statue of Buddha from Sultanganj, depicting the Dharma Chakra Pravartan Mudra, with intricately sculpted deer and chakra.</li>
                    <li><b>Lord Ganesha Statues:</b> Two statues from Mandar, showcasing Ganesha with six hands, holding various symbolic items.</li>
                    <li><b>Mahishasurmardini Idol:</b> A magnificent black stone statue from Banka, depicting the goddess Mahishasurmardini with ten hands, most of which are now broken.</li>
                    <li><b>Maa Durga Idol:</b> A statue of Chaturbhuj Durga from the CMS School area, riding a lion and holding a snake, Khadag, and Dhal, adorned with intricate jewelry.</li>
                    <li><b>Lord Vishnu Idols:</b> Various statues of Lord Vishnu, including Varah Vishnu and Garuda Vishnu, highlighting different aspects of the deity as described in Vishnu Purana and other ancient texts.</li>
                    <li><b>Yakshini Statue:</b> An ancient and beautifully crafted statue from Shahkund, depicting a Yakshini with intricate details on the wrists and arms.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

